  <datafield tag="545" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Church organization established to faciliate interdenominational cooperation and to promote ecumenical action on issues of social concern. Succeeded the Michigan Council of Churches, a Protestant interdenominational organization founded in 1928 and merged in 1936 with the Michigan Council of religious Education (originally named the Michigan Sunday School Association).</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Records reflect the large-scale cooperation between various Christian denominations as well as ecumenical activities related to evangelical missions, Christian education, and pressing social issues. Administrative records, meeting minutes, and newsletters document governing bodies, committees, and general assemblies while planning and meeting materials, correspondence, and reports detail the organization's involvement with initiatives regarding the Vietnam war, peace education, environmentalism, racism, social justice, and ministry and outreach to Native Americans, migrant workers, and rural communities. Also includes photographs of various officers, meetings, and events.</subfield>
  </datafield>
